			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I first discovered the SkiNets.com group when I went to Alpe d&#8217;Huez last season. Its ADH website, <a href="http://www.alpedhueznet.com/" target="_blank">http://www.alpedhueznet.com/</a>, was by far the best and most informative resort site I could find, beating even the official one. I didn&#8217;t quite realise it initially, but the above site was part of a much larger group that covers resorts throughout France and Switzerland.</p>
<p>Better yet, each resort has its own individual App for iOS &#8211; a bonus given that I&#8217;m heading to Val Thorens this season. The Apps are, essentially, the website in an easier to digest form. The home page gives you a quick resort overview &#8211; the weather for the next 3 days, when the last snowfall was, the number of pistes open, and the avalanche hazard. There&#8217;s also a news section providing tips and warnings regarding the weather, heavy traffic, and other considerations required when adventuring abroad for alpine action.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<a href='http://howardlloyd.co.uk/2011/09/friday-app-focus-3-skinets-com/image/' title='Resort Overview'><img width="150" height="150" src="http://howardlloyd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/image-150x150.png" class="attachment-thumbnail" alt="Resort Overview" title="Resort Overview" /></a>
<a href='http://howardlloyd.co.uk/2011/09/friday-app-focus-3-skinets-com/image-1/' title='News'><img width="150" height="150" src="http://howardlloyd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/image-1-150x150.png" class="attachment-thumbnail" alt="News" title="News" /></a>
<a href='http://howardlloyd.co.uk/2011/09/friday-app-focus-3-skinets-com/image-2/' title='image (2)'><img width="150" height="150" src="http://howardlloyd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/image-2-150x150.png" class="attachment-thumbnail" alt="image (2)" title="image (2)" /></a>

<p>The Forecast pane gives more detailed information, including the wind speed and direction, the wind chill factor (which is much more important in a ski resort than it is in everyday life), the min and max temps, and the outlook. What&#8217;s more, this data is provided by <a href="www.snow-forecast.com " target="_blank">www.snow-forecast.com </a>(the subject of my previous post), so it&#8217;s guaranteed to be the best available report.</p>
<p>The remaining pane, &#8220;More&#8221;, contains a variety of useful tools. There are maps for both the piste and the resort; personally, I&#8217;m a fan of the traditional paper fold-out variety, but it&#8217;s nice knowing I have an easily-accessible piste map should I lose it. There&#8217;s an emergency contacts section (a feature which, I hope, I never have to use) listing the numbers for the Tourist Office, Mountain Rescue, Doctor, Police and Fire/Rescue services.</p>
<p>Finally, there&#8217;s the usual webcams section (providing the resort has them), which can be useful to determine whether it&#8217;s worth trekking to the other side of the mountain.</p>
<p>The main drawback of these Apps is that they&#8217;re resort-specific. I had to purchase the Alpe d&#8217;Huez App last season, and had to spend another £0.69 this year for the Val Thorens version &#8211; nothing bank-breaking, but it&#8217;s a slight annoyance.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;re not heading to any of the supported resorts (listed below), the above will be of no real use to you, but if you are I&#8217;d most definitely recommend grabbing the related App. They&#8217;re all available on the <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/valthonet/id352756861?mt=8" target="_blank">App Store</a>, and you can follow them on Twitter here: <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/skinets" target="_blank">@skinets</a></p>
<p>Supported Resorts:</p>
<ul>
<li>Alpe d&#8217;Huez</li>
<li>Avoriaz</li>
<li>Chamonix</li>
<li>Courchevel</li>
<li>La Plagne</li>
<li>Les 2 Alps</li>
<li>Les Arcs</li>
<li>Meribel</li>
<li>Morzine &amp; Les Gets</li>
<li>Tignes</li>
<li>Val d&#8217;Isere</li>
<li>Val Thorens</li>
<li>Verbier (Switzerland)</li>
</ul>

