		<description><![CDATA[<p>Every Friday, starting today, I’ll be recommending an App I typically use while on skiing/boarding trips. Where possible, I’ll supplement the post with screenshots from my own iPhone, but for some apps you’ll have to make do with regular screenshots.</p> <p>So, first up is the wonderful Ski Tracks. Taking advantage of the iPhone’s GPS capabilities, [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Every Friday, starting today, I’ll be recommending an App I typically use while on skiing/boarding trips. Where possible, I’ll supplement the post with screenshots from my own iPhone, but for some apps you’ll have to make do with regular screenshots.</p>
<p>So, first up is the wonderful Ski Tracks. Taking advantage of the iPhone’s GPS capabilities, Ski Tracks presents an easy, yet powerful way of tracking your distance covered, maximum speed, number of runs, and other various statistics. I have used Ski Tracks on a number of trips now, and it’s always interesting to see the raw data for your outdoor adventures.</p>
<p>Your runs are broken down into stages; it’ll stop tracking your speed when it detects you’re going uphill, ie. you’re on a chair or gondola. It’s possible to see what time you started and finished, your maximum and average speeds, the distance covered, the vertical descent, and the maximum slope angle.<br />
Another feature is the ability to see your run on a Google map of the area. It plots the various stages for you, and is a great way to see just which runs were getting most of your attention.</p>
<p>The final track review feature are two graphs (altitude and speed) plotted against time, so you can see how your day progressed.</p>
<p>The below is a screenshot of my penultimate day in Ischgl, Austria last season. I should point out that I was on skis, not boarding, hence the higher speed.</p>
<div id="attachment_745" class="wp-caption aligncenter" style="width: 352px"><a href="http://howardlloyd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/VteLe.jpeg" rel="lightbox[744]"><img class="size-full wp-image-745 " title="Ski Tracks Ischgl" src="http://howardlloyd.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/VteLe.jpeg" alt="" width="342" height="512" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">New Personal Skiing Speed Record in Ischgl, Austria. March 2011</p></div>
<p>I tend to start Ski Tracks in the morning, and either opt to let it run throughout the day, or I’ll pause it while on extended breaks (e.g. eating lunch). Having one track for a whole day makes the reviewing statistics process a lot easier.</p>
<p>Rather handily, you’re able to set a battery percentage level where it’ll stop both tracking and music playback, so you don’t have to worry about being without a phone in the evening.</p>
<p>I’d say Ski Tracks is one of my essential, must-have apps for when I’m snowboarding. It’s a great way to encourage healthy competition between you and your buddies (who can go the fastest/who covered the most distance, etc), and is a great way of reflecting on the day’s events.</p>
<p>There are other apps out there (including Powderful, which I quite liked) that do the same job, but I’ve found Ski Tracks to be the best of the bunch.</p>
<p>Ski Tracks is available on the <a href="http://itunes.apple.com/gb/app/ski-tracks-gps-track-recorder/id365724094?mt=8" target="_blank">App Store</a>.</p>

