		<description><![CDATA[<p>With the 2011/12 Winter season fast approaching, many people begin to research trips, buy gear, check flights and prepare their legs and livers. Over the years, as my interest has switched from skiing to snowboarding, so, too, have the websites that I’ve traditionally used in the past. However, a ‘core’ set of sites remain, and [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>With the 2011/12 Winter season fast approaching, many people begin to research trips, buy gear, check flights and prepare their legs and livers. Over the years, as my interest has switched from skiing to snowboarding, so, too, have the websites that I’ve traditionally used in the past. However, a ‘core’ set of sites remain, and I’ll be listing these below.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h4>Packages/Transport/Hotels<span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px;"> </span></h4>
<p>My Dad, like many other Brits, has always used Inghams, Crystal, or Thomson Ski to research and book his skiing trips. However, I have long maintained that they don’t present good value for money. Therefore, I set my Dad a challenge: research and spec a trip to Val Thorens for 3 people, and see if he could beat a package I could put together. I can’t remember specifics, but I managed to find a better hotel, better flight times from a closer airport, with the luxury of our own rental car, for roughly £200 pounds cheaper.</p>
<p>So, the sites. I’m sure there are many other (good) alternative options, but I typically use the following:</p>
<p>Flights: <a href="http://www.skyscanner.net">www.skyscanner.net</a></p>
<p>Hotels: <a href="http://www.hotels.com">www.hotels.com</a>, <a href="http://www.booking.com">www.booking.com</a>, Google for “accommodation in &lt;resort&gt;”</p>
<p>Packages: <a href="http://www.directski.com">www.directski.com</a> &#8211; these guys managed to find accommodation, flights and transfers to Mayrhofen for much less than I could spec together.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h4>Gear<span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px;"> </span></h4>
<p>Living in the UK presents a problem: a lot of the big US snowboard companies don’t have established retail POS locations, and some (including Burton) don’t have an online store for anything but clothing and accessories. There are the traditional UK chains that do offer hardware, Snow&amp;Rock and Ellis Brigham being the obvious two, but I’ve found alternative options have always served me better.</p>
<p>Gear: <a href="http://www.blue-tomato.com">www.blue-tomato.com</a> &#8211; One of the first retailers in Europe to stock the new Burton stuff when it launched on Saturday 14th August, and as a result they got my money. Speedy shipping from Austria, too.</p>
<p>Ski wear: <a href="http://www.simplypiste.com">www.simplypiste.com</a> &#8211; These guys stock a large range of gear, and their customer service is fantastic. Recommended.</p>
<p>Goggles: <a href="http://www.rxsport.co.uk/">http://www.rxsport.co.uk/</a></p>
<p>Burton-specific: <a href="http://www.weloveburtonsnowboards.com/">http://www.weloveburtonsnowboards.com/</a></p>
<h4></h4>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h4>Information<span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-size: 14px; line-height: 22px;"> </span></h4>
<p>It’s sometimes difficult to find good, reliable information, but I’ve always sworn by the Where to Ski and Snowboard book. The website (<a href="http://www.wheretoskiandsnowboard.com/">http://www.wheretoskiandsnowboard.com/</a>), while good, is nowhere near as good as the book. It’s well regarded as one of the snow bibles &#8211; go buy it.</p>
<p>However, outside of this, I’ve always found good information from Snowboard Club UK (<a href="http://www.snowboardclub.co.uk">www.snowboardclub.co.uk</a>), Gone Boarding (<a href="http://www.goneboarding.co.uk">www.goneboarding.co.uk</a>) and Snowboarding Forum (<a href="http://www.snowboardingforum.com">www.snowboardingforum.com</a>)</p>

